Deceased","1646–Male":"1646–Deceased","1610–Male":"1610–Deceased","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mattheis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernd, Erwin, Ewald, Friedrich.","German: from a variant of the personal name <i>Matthäus</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Philip Mattheis was born in 1610. He had at least 1 son with Wilheminah Kitgiel."},"et":{"1610–":"1610–Surnud","1611–Female":"1611–Surnud","1646–Male":"1646–Surnud","1610–Male":"1610–Surnud","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1610–":"1610–Kuollut","1611–Female":"1611–Kuollut","1646–Male":"1646–Kuollut","1610–Male":"1610–Kuollut","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Saksa"},"fr":{"1610–":"1610–Décédé","1611–Female":"1611–Décédée","1646–Male":"1646–Décédé","1610–Male":"1610–Décédé","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Philip Mattheis est né en 1610. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Wilheminah Kitgiel."},"de":{"1610–":"1610–Verstorben","1611–Female":"1611–Verstorben","1646–Male":"1646–Verstorben","1610–Male":"1610–Verstorben","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Deutschland","lifeSummary":"Philip Mattheis wurde 1610 geboren. Er hatte mit Wilheminah Kitgiel mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1610–":"1610–Desede","1611–Female":"1611–Desede","1646–Male":"1646–Desede","1610–Male":"1610–Desede","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, Hoxter-Nordrhein-Westfalen, Germany":"Allemagne"},"hu":{"1610–":"1610–elhunyt","1611–Female":"1611–elhunyt","1646–Male":"1646–elhunyt","1610–Male":"1610–elhunyt","1646":"1646","1611":"1611","1610":"1610","Hertstelle, H